article.description: Ohio State has embraced Jim Foster's philosophy -- play hard, play clean and defend.
article.headline: Wilburn scores 19 points as Buckeyes advance
article.linkText: Defense the key as Ohio State puts away Weber State
article.story:
RUSTON, La. (AP) -- Ohio State has taken first-year coach Jim
Foster's philosophy to heart -- play hard, play clean and defend.

	   Led by Kim Wilburn's 19 points, Ohio State beat Weber
State 66-44 in the first round of the NCAA West Regional on Sunday
night.

	   Ohio State, 14-15 last season, is in the NCAA Tournament for the
first time since 1999. It's the 18th trip to the NCAA Tournament for Foster, who also coached at St. Joseph and Vanderbilt.

	   Ohio State (22-9) did exactly what Foster has urged all season -- played tough defense. The Buckeyes held opponents to a Big Ten
league-best 57.4 points a game. They allowed Weber to shoot only
33 percent (17-for-52).

	   ''We were aware of where their real good shooters were and we
played intelligently,'' Foster said.

	   Weber State (21-9) could not cope with the bigger Buckeyes, who
outrebounded them 39-25 and shot 50 percent from the field (25-for-50).

	   ''We're not the first team to struggle against them to try to
find a way to score,'' said Weber State coach Carla Taylor.

	   Courtney Coleman scored 13 points for Ohio State and LaToya
Turner added 12.

	   Julie Gjertsen led Weber State with 18 points.

	   ''Their matchup was real good,'' Gjertsen said. ''We threw
everything at them we could. We had open looks. It wasn't like it
was impossible. We just didn't score.''

	   Ohio State was whistled for only nine fouls to Weber State's 16. The
Buckeyes hit 14 of 18 free throws The Wildcats did not get to the
free throw line until the 8:59 mark of the second half when
Gjertsen made two.

	   ''We're quick, but we don't foul a lot,'' Foster said.

	   Three of the Ohio State starters were 6-foot or better, Weber
State's 6-foot starter was Angela Sampson. Wilburn was one of the
smallest players on either team at 5-6.

	   Ohio State held a 29-15 lead at halftime.

	   Weber State was making its second consecutive tournament
appearance.
